  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - ROGUE</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>PLAY WELL WITH OTHERS</font> - <small>Shalen, Bristlebaine</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Okay I will now discuss some great rogue team up options and how to work well with other players.<p>

There are several classes I love teaming up with, enchanters, shaman, and bards.  I will discuss some
tactics with these classes.<p>

Shaman are great, they are pretty good at fighting, and wear a good amount of armor, and in my
opinion are the best buffers in the game.  Group with a Shaman and prepare to feel like a god as they lay buff after buff
upon you.<p?

Shamen are also great to work with becasue they have a good ammount of spells that really tick off the monsters.  If evade ever fails or the bad guys just decides to stick to you, stop attacking and tell um to make it mad.  1, 2, 3, easy.

At lvl 13 I grouped with a lvl 13 troll shamen in the Oasis of Marr.  While everone else our level was grouping with a full 6 killing crocks, getting horrid loot and exp, we were at the orc highway raking both exp and money in.<p>  

She would med by the zone, and sense I had a sow I could backstab pull, so I put away my bow.  I would find a white yellow or red orc, then hide and sneak, rail it in the back for 40 damage, unsneak and run back to her.  She would cast when
I got close so the monster was on her, I would backstab again.<p>

After the monster died, which took minimal time and mana, she would med as I looked for our next target and let her troll regen heal her up.  We gained a level and a half in such a short time I nearly cried when we had to part company, but she was dying for her new spells.<p>

Working with a bard is really easy too.  They have more hit points then you, can wear better armor then you, and their songs really tick monsters off.
If they play certain songs, like hymm of restoration, you never have to worry about a monster on you.  It's just backstab backstab. <p>

They have selo's for a fast exit or travel, they have hymm which will heal you faster then fast, their
battle buffs add ac, str, and have haste effects.  They make amazing fighting buddies, and generally love screwing around as much as I do.<p>

Alright now onto my absolute favorite class to play with, the Enchanter.  These benders of minds are more important to me in a party then any other.  I like a good enchanter as much as a tank loves a good healer.<p>

There are some great techniques to use with enchanters and I will discuss a few.<p>

Enchanters with a pet.<p>

Start off combat with the enchanter casting Tashan on the bad guy.  Let the monster hit the enchanter once so the pet will engage (Enchanter pets are
command less) then get it off him/her with a good backstab.  The enchanter then fears that bad boy and both you and the pet chase wacking and backstabbing it till it dies.  Enchanters do this solo, so add a rogue and the process is faster with backstab, and more mana efficient cause the enchanter normally
doesn't have to re-fear because of your massive damage and the tashan starter spell.<p>

Okay now enchanters without pets and on a camp.<p>

Your at a camp with 3 monsters.  The enchanter mezzes the mobs, he/she tashans one then charms.  You barrel off into combat backstabbing which ever one the enchanter's new pet is attacking.  You now have a disposable tank.  Make sure you constantly evade and let the monster
opposite you take all the blows.  If ever you anger the monster too badly and it
won't turn off the pet, the enchanter then can memory blur to make it forget about you.<p>

After your first target is dead the other is, or is close to, waking up from mezz.  You and the pet kick it's
rear, the pet will probably die here or break charm, where you then kill it in one stroke with backstab cause it is so hurt from tanking.<p>

If at anytime the pet breaks charm don't worry about pulling it off the enchanter unless they ask, they are used to this happening, and will probably stun it, then re-charm, or stun it and tashan and charm the other at full health.<p>

Basically you have no worries with an enchanter, they are so wonderful because of it.  And they have no worries
about their mega taunt spells cause of you mega taunt backstab.<p>

Now onto enchanters with no pets and one target.<p>

Funny, but one bad guy is harder to an enchanter then two, but with a rogue you'll
easily make quick work of some real nasty opponents.  All because of their stun spells.<p>

Stun is like a short mezz, but it is NOT interrupted by combat.  The enchanter ticks something off with a dd spell or tashan, when the
beastie gets close, they stun it.  Now it's your turn to backstab it and wack it a few times in the back.
It awakes and turns to face you, let them stun it again, then whip around to it's back and backstab it again.  Back and forth back and forth, all the while both of you take nearly 0 damage.  <p>

Not all that mana effective, but man can you raise some backstab skill fast with it.<p?

You will quickly get used to working with thier charms, stuns, memory blurs, and mezzes.  And anyone who works well with an enchanter is a welcome member to any party.<p>

These have just been a few combinations of team-ups and you can use the techniques I have described in full groups too.  Basically a rogue is a great addition to any party or individual as long as that person is not a pure melee type (lots of sitting on the ground).  <p>

</td></tr>
